metadata.name: Reunion #101
metadata.description:
Reunion

---------------

Controls:
S: Export image at current scale
1-6: Change image scale (for higher quality downloads; default: 1)
F: Fit to screen (note that this can change the piece considerably; default: off)
G: Toggle grain (default: on)
O: Toggle border (default: off)
D: Toggle distortion (default: on)
A: Toggle chromatic abberation (default: on)
C: Toggle circles (default: on)
B: Toggle reversed B-side (default: off)

---------------

Outputs are generated using the minter's address as a seed. Each wallet is given a set of 25 seeds to look through. These are the only outputs that wallet can mint. Take your time and pick your favorite

---------------

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #190
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Make-believe #4
metadata.description:
#genuary32nd – Let's meet on this make-believe date, in this make-believe place.
I’m having déjà vu, or is it a memory?

This artwork is originally created for the genuary2023 prompt "Art Deco", using the same core algorithm as Memory Module. Made with fractal math and p5js.

Keyboard controls:
[s] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[g] Toggle texture.

URL params:
&aspect=[aspect ratio, eg 2]
&res=[resolution multiplier, 0.5-8]

Created by Elsif, 2023.02

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Blurevich #359
metadata.description:
"Blurevich"

The painting is characterized by its non-representational style, where the rectangles are not meant to depict recognizable objects or figures. 
Instead, the blurred rectangles serve as visual elements that create a sense of movement and dynamism in the painting. 
The use of blurriness in the rectangles gives the painting a hazy and ethereal quality. 
The colors used in the painting would  be bold and striking, creating a striking contrast between the sharp edges of the rectangles and the soft, blurred edges. 
The overall effect of the painting is one of abstraction and experimentation, express our emotions.

metadata.name: Lua #56
metadata.description:
"I journey to the world of the moon,
Where life is less burdensome,
Where all gaze upon me, unaware
Of my presence in this lunar realm.

Yet darkness occasionally envelops me,
Leaves me lost and unsure.
But in the end, it is worth it all,
For on the moon, I am admired and loved,
Connected to others, despite being unseen."

~ Eduxdux + GPT

Made with p5.js, chroma.js and p5.grain

metadata.name: Circumscript #31
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #192
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Monotipia #62
metadata.description:
Graphic compositions made with simple elements. Playing with the subtlety and rhythm of colors, shapes and textures.

This work was inspired by the textures of monotype prints and those of metal engraving. Especially in the geometric marks made by the inking roller while stretching the graphic ink to make a manual printing. It is a tribute to the visuality of handmade prints.

"Monotipia" means monotype printing in Portuguese. It is a graphic printing process that results in a single copy. Here I make a parallel between monotype printing and the code+hash minting process, which also produces a single image.

---
Features:
-> 15 composition schemes
-> 51 handpicked base colors
-> 3 canvas formats:  
-----> Portrait (vertical) 
-----> Square 
-----> Landscape (horizontal)
-> 3 element tones options: 
-----> Light Texture & Shapes
-----> Light Texture / Dark Shapes 
-----> Dark Texture & Shapes

---
To save the image as a png file, type:
[1] save at actual size 
[2] save with 2000px height
[3] save with 3000px height
[4] save with 4000px height
[5] save with 5000px height

Depending on the size option, the render time can be long.

---
Created with p5.js

---
This is my first project on FX(hash) and I would like to express my special thanks to Janaina Selva, Dmarchi, Gyo and Morbeck for their support and for following the step-by-step development of this work, always contributing with a critical eye and great suggestions. I also thank the help from the FX(hash) community on Discord.

---
(c) Marcelo Terça-Nada, 2023
https://marcelonada.redezero.org/
@marcelonada

metadata.name: Paysages Chromatiques A #4
metadata.description:
Taking my inspiration from impressionist and contemporary paintings, I tried to generate 
mixtures of more or less superimposed colors, creating flowing effects or spots as one
would obtain with paint.
This work is the first in a two-part series featuring abstraction and imagination.
I hope it will inspire you to take the time to daydream, or simply to spend a moment 
where the mind can wander freely through the colors.

To save a png file type [s]
TO remove the texture type [t]

To render at higher resolution add &pd=2 at the end of the url in live mode
(others values are valid too but be patient the rendering can be long)
---
100% code made with p5js and glsl
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.
---
Hervé (23 nov)
